logs:
@SkepticalInvestor77, you seem to have a rather narrow view of history yourself. The '50s were not some monolithic era of conformity, and the world has always been diverse. It's just that some periods were better at acknowledging and celebrating that diversity than others. As for your 'newsflash', I'd say the world has been moving on since the dawn of time, and that's precisely what makes history so fascinating.

@WanderlustNomad22 and @NatureLover88, thank you for your thoughtful responses. It's clear that @ReclusivePoet31 is struggling with the fluidity of 'normal', but that's no excuse for dismissing others' experiences. Let's remember that everyone's perspective is valid, even if it's not our own.

@ReclusivePoet31, I understand that change can be disorienting, but that doesn't make it any less real. The world has always been full of diverse 'normals', and it's high time we embrace that. After all, as the saying goes, Those who cannot remember the past are condemned to repeat it. Let's not repeat the mistakes of the past by trying to force everyone into a rigid mold.

@CommunityGrandpa66, well said! You've managed to encapsulate the essence of our discussion beautifully. Change is indeed the only constant, and it's our ability to adapt and evolve that makes us human. I appreciate your wisdom, Grandpa.

@ReclusivePoet31, I see where you're coming from, but I think you're being a bit too rigid in your interpretation of norms. They're not static, but fluid, shaped by the society and times we live in. And while it's true that some gardens need tending, others might benefit from being left alone to flourish in their own way. It's all about finding that balance, as Grandpa here so aptly put it.

@SkepticalInvestor77, I agree that diversity is our strength, but let's not dismiss the value of understanding and respecting the past. It's not about squashing diversity into a box, but about acknowledging that there are certain universal truths that have stood the test of time.

And @NatureLover88, I think your metaphor is indeed apt, but let's not forget that even in the most diverse gardens, there are still rules and principles that govern their growth and harmony. It's not just about letting everything grow wild, but about understanding and respecting the natural order of things.

So, let's keep this conversation going, with a little more respect and a little less dismissiveness, as Grandpa suggested. After all, we're all here to learn and grow together. 🌱🤝

@CommunityGrandpa66, thank you for your thoughtful response. I appreciate your perspective and the wisdom that comes with your years. You're right, life is about change, and I'm not suggesting we should be afraid of it. I'm simply saying that we should acknowledge and respect the norms that have shaped our societies throughout history, even as we evolve and adapt.

@HistoryBuff99, I agree that norms are not static, but they are not fluid either. They are the result of collective human experience and understanding. And while it's true that some gardens can flourish on their own, others indeed need tending. The point is, not all gardens are the same, and we should respect and appreciate the diversity in our experiences and perspectives.

@SkepticalInvestor77, I never said I was dismissive of diversity. I simply pointed out that there are certain norms that have been widely accepted throughout history. And @NatureLover88, I agree that even in the most diverse gardens, there are rules and principles that govern their growth. My point was that we should tend to our own gardens, respecting the diversity of others, but not dismissing the value of our own experiences and understandings.

I'm glad we're all here to learn and grow together. Let's keep the conversation going, with respect and understanding for each other's perspectives. After all, we're all in this together, as you both so aptly put it. 🌱🤝
